<subSubSection pageId="187" pageNumber="466" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="187.[2010,2607,1631,2054]" lastBlockId="187.[1400,2608,2060,2724]" pageId="187" pageNumber="466">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[2013,2299,1903,1936]" pageId="187" pageNumber="466">Descriptive notes.</emphasis>
Head-body 97-126 mm, tail 77-91 mm, ear 13-16 mm, hindfoot 23-25 mm; weight 30-44 g. See general characters of the genus under the Amazonian Hocicudo (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hershkovitz" authorityYear="1994" box="[1732,1923,2060,2093]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Oxymycterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="187" pageNumber="466" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="amazonicus">O. amazonicus</taxonomicName>
) account. The Small Yungas Hocicudo is a small species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1837" box="[1547,1704,2100,2133]" class="Mammalia" family="Cricetidae" genus="Oxymycterus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="187" pageNumber="466" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Oxymycterus</taxonomicName>
. Dorsum is blackish gray (darker in younger individuals); venter is tipped ocherous; and hairs are short, glossy, and fine. Tail and skin of dorsal and palmar surfaces are blackish brown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="187" pageNumber="466" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="187.[1400,2608,2060,2724]" pageId="187" pageNumber="466">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1401,1512,2218,2251]" pageId="187" pageNumber="466">Habitat.</emphasis>
Mostly montane humid forest dominated by epiphyte-laden trees, 
<taxonomicName authority="(Urticacea)" baseAuthorityName="Urticacea" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Urticaceae" genus="Cecropia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="187" pageNumber="466" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Cecropia (Urticacea)</taxonomicName>
, bamboos, and tree ferns and 
<taxonomicName box="[2000,2107,2262,2291]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" genus="Polylepis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="187" pageNumber="466" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Polylepis</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[2128,2259,2262,2291]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Rosaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Rosales" pageId="187" pageNumber="466" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Rosaceae</taxonomicName>
) woodland at elevations of 600-3500 m. The Small Yungas Hocicudo is found in mossy runways, under logs, and around tree roots.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="187" pageNumber="466" type="food_feeding">
<paragraph blockId="187.[1400,2608,2060,2724]" pageId="187" pageNumber="466">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1401,1668,2376,2409]" pageId="187" pageNumber="466">Food and Feeding.</emphasis>
The Small Yungas Hocicudo mainly eats insects and other invertebrates.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="187" pageNumber="466" type="breeding">
<paragraph blockId="187.[1400,2608,2060,2724]" pageId="187" pageNumber="466">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1401,1536,2454,2487]" pageId="187" pageNumber="466">Breeding.</emphasis>
Female Small Yungas Hocicudos showed signs of breeding at the end of rainy season (March-April).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
